article.description: Lauren Jackson had 32 points and 12 rebounds to lead the Seattle Storm to a 75-61 victory over the Sacramento Monarchs on Saturday night.
article.headline: Seattle star nets third double-double of '04
article.linkText: Jackson, Storm pour it on in rout of Monarchs
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Lauren Jackson had 11 points before the
Sacramento Monarchs scored their first, sending the Seattle Storm
on their way to a lopsided victory.

Jackson finished with 32 points and 12 rebounds, and Seattle
beat Sacramento 75-61 Saturday night.

Last season's WNBA MVP scored 23 points in the first half to set
a team record and notched her third double-double of the season. It
was her 67th straight double-figure scoring game.

"It wasn't my perfect game, but it was a good one," said
Jackson, who was 8-for-19 from the field and 13-for-15 from the
free-throw line. "It wasn't great, and I can do better."

She looked great to teammate Sue Bird.

"When she's going like that, you just want to get her the ball
because she's like a machine out there," said Bird, who added 16
points and six assists.

Jackson outscored the entire Sacramento starting five by six
points.

Sacramento had its three-game winning streak snapped, allowing
Seattle to hit 61.5 percent from the floor in the first half.

"You have to give Seattle credit. We've been playing well
defensively for the last five games," Monarchs coach John
Whisenant said. "We have no fatigue excuses so that wasn't a
factor. They just played well. They were ready to go and attacked
us."

The Storm never trailed, and led by as much as 30, 69-39, with
9:53 to play in the second half.

"I know the coach was a little upset with us that we didn't win
by 30," Bird said, "but that will be the only negative we take
from this."

Sheri Sam added 11 for the Storm.

Reserve Hamchetou Maiga scored 17 to lead the Monarchs, and
rookie Rebekkah Brunson matched her career high with 10 points.

Jackson hit three 3-pointers and a pair of free throws as
Seattle jumped out to an 11-0 lead in the first 4:13.

The Storm run was stopped on a driving layup by DeMaya Walker
with 15:21 left in the half.

Seattle led 49-32 at halftime.

"We had pretty good offensive execution until the last 10 or 12
minutes," Storm coach Anne Donovan said. "I think Lauren hitting
those first three 3s helped us get a cushion."

The two teams combined to commit 41 turnovers, and the 21 by the
Monarchs was a season high.
